(Remember $z$ is a root of $f(x) = x^{3} - x + 1$, if $f(z) = 0$.)

By Newton's method, we can improve on our guess for a root to the
equation, by computing the following:

\begin{align*}
x_{1} = x_{0} - \frac{f(x_{0})}{f'(x_{0})}
\end{align*} where $x_{1}$ is our
improved guess and $f(x) = x^{3} - x + 1$. Performing the computation
gives:

\begin{align*}
x_{1} &= (-1) - \frac{f(-1)}{f'(-1)} = -1 - \frac{(-1)^{3} - (-1) + 1}{3(-1)^{2} - 1} = -\frac{3}{2}.
\end{align*} Therefore, our improved estimate for the root of
$f(x) = x^{3} - x + 1$ is:

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}x_{1} =-\frac{3}{2}}
\end{align*}
